<TEXT>
a practice space shuttle countdown 
was under way here today in a test leading to a firing of 
discoverys three main engines on the launch pad saturday 
the launch team started the count at 1133 pm sunday on 
wednesday it planned to load more than a half million gallons of 
liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen propellant into the shuttles 
external fuel tank 
it will be the first time a shuttle has been fueled since the 
challenger explosion which killed seven astronauts on jan 28 
1986 
when the countdown reaches 10 seconds before a mock liftoff on 
wednesday a problem will be simulated to force a launch 
postponement then launch crews will rehearse whats called a 
72hour turnaround 
they will empty the fuel tank start another countdown refill 
the tank and aim for a 20second test firing of discoverys main 
engines at 730 am saturday 
the firing with the shuttle bolted firmly on the pad will 
check modifications made to the engines and is considered critical 
to discovery being certified for the first postchallenger shuttle 
flight 
the launch with a fiveman crew is scheduled for early 
september but the date is in doubt as engineers continue to puzzle 
over how to fix a small gas leak in a steering engine system that 
is separate from the main engines 
they hope to make the repair on the pad and avoid rolling 
discovery back to a hangar a move that could delay the flight as 
much as two months 
experts are considering several ways to reach the inaccessible 
leak including cutting a hole through the shuttles cargo bay wall 
and running a snakelike tube through the gas line in an effort to 
plug it 
the national aeronautics and space administration said it will 
not make a decision on whether to move discovery off the pad until 
after the main engine test firing 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

