<TEXT>
it takes more than 12 hours of 
practice a day under blazing sun or summer rain to get the 
precision right 
but any student who wants to be in the garfield cadets drum and 
bugle corps knows that is the kind of summer 500 will buy 
its a lot like marine corps boot camp said 19yearold 
dennis klophaus a firstyear corps member from jacksonville nc 
the 54yearold corps headquartered in the northern new jersey 
city of garfield is made up of student musicians ages 14 to 21 
from across the united states and canada 
the cadets are the current drum corp international champions 
next month they will try for an unprecedented fifth dci world 
championship as they compete against 70 other corps in kansas city 
until then the garfield cadets who number about 100 will don 
their maroon and offwhite uniforms and strut their stuff across 
eight states and canada as they complete the second half of their 
summer 1988 tour 
the biggest thing that makes them special is the type of 
training said marc sylvester a visual instructor its very 
extreme 
sylvester 30 stands on the bleachers during practice to make 
sure the cadets presentations are pleasing to the eye 
the type of work and pressure they go through is similar to 
what someone in their age group would do when trying out for the 
olympics sylvester said the prestige of winning is like 
winning a gold medal 
george hopkins the groups executive director since 1982 said 
the corps challenges itself by purposely bypassing anything that 
might come easily in favor of the most difficult routines 
if we know that we can do it then we will not do it 
hopkins said 
a day at training camp in this northern new jersey community 
begins at 730 am when the corps rises eats breakfast and 
starts practicing no later than 830 
about 230 pm they eat again they return to practice a half 
hour later dinner is served at 630 pm then the cadets are back 
at work for three more hours 
theyre free until lights out at 11 but often spend the time 
discussing improvements for the routine said tom hawrylko a corps 
spokesman 
all this including bedding down on gymnasium floors costs 
500 which the cadets pay as a membership fee 
i wanted to learn what hard work is and what it does to you 
said firstyear cadet david geltch of washington crossing pa 
its made me concentrate more 
mark poquis a 20yearold baritone horn player from burke va 
said i learned that no matter how downhill and exhausted you 
are you can still push yourself that extra step it builds 
character 
following the cadets from city to city is an 18wheel truck that 
carries food and other supplies another 18wheeler carries the 
instruments along with the streamers and flags for the color 
guard four buses transport the cadets vans carry instructors and 
support staff and a 24foot promotional bus tags along 
like most other drum and bugle corps the garfield cadets raise 
money with cake sales car washes donations and raffles along 
with membership fees the corps has an annual budget of 450000 to 
500000 said gregory pych a member of the board of directors 
this year however the cadets received their first corporate 
sponsorship from k mart stores and emerson radio pych said he 
said exact figures were not available 
besides becoming better musicians the cadets are taught good 
competitive manners sylvester said 
you never are a sore loser or an obnoxious winner he said 
