<TEXT>
a special ruling party congress today 
accepted the resignation of strongman ne win but rejected his call 
for a referendum that could have ended 26 years of oneparty rule 
a congress delegate said 
official rangoon radio however said only that ne wins 
resignation had been debated by the delegates and did not indicate 
what action if any was reached 
the delegate who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
ruling burma socialist program party congress agreed to accept the 
resignations of ne win as party chief and san yu as the vice 
chairman but to retain them as inactive members 
burmese analysts suggested that the vagueness of the official 
radio broadcast reflected divisions within party ranks 
the broadcast said the 1061 party delegates empowered the 
partys central committee to evaluate a sweeping proposal for 
economic reform but it gave no indication of whether any of the 
new measures had been accepted 
the threeday congress of the ruling burma socialist program 
party has been considering dramatic changes in a statecontrolled 
economic system that turned a potentially prosperous country into a 
debtridden povertystricken nation 
the key architect of the system ne win tendered his 
resignation saturday as chairman of the party and offered to remove 
himself from political life five other top leaders likewise 
submitted resignations 
state radio announced sunday that an emergency session of 
parliament would convene wednesday apparently to act on ne wins 
proposal of holding a referendum on whether burma should scrap a 
quarter century of oneparty rule in favor of a multiparty system 
the emergency session could also deal with the appointment of 
new government leaders to replace the five who are resigning the 
five including president san yu held government posts in addition 
to their party positions 
prime minister maung maung kha one of the few top leaders not 
on the resignation roll was expected to be named today to replace 
the 77yearold ne win as chairman of the ruling party 
the sudden and generally unexpected changes come in wake of 
bloody antigovernment riots and worsening economic conditions in 
the isolationist southeast asian nation 
the official radio broadcasting from the congress carried 
speeches of several among the more than 1000 delegates asking ne 
win to reconsider his retirement until success has been 
achieved 
indeed some western diplomats doubt that ne win who has held 
undisputed power for 26 years will desist from interference in 
the future party and the organization of the new government 
not only did the former military chief who seized power in a 
1962 coup crush antigovernment opposition that occasionally 
flared he also moved against leaders within his own ranks when 
they exhibited too much promise and independence 
this has left a leadership vacuum in rangoon that may prove 
difficult to fill if there is a wholesale removal of officials from 
party and government ranks as ne win indicated 
maung maung kha who assumed the prime ministership in 1977 has 
to date not exhibited any particular dynamism or vision that would 
be necessary to implement the wideranging reforms being debated by 
the congress 
