<TEXT>
former rep robert n mcclory an illinois 
republican reluctantly thrust into the national spotlight for his 
role in impeachment proceedings against president richard nixon is 
dead at age 80 
mcclory who represented the chicago suburbs in congress for 20 
years until 1982 collapsed at church sunday and died a short time 
later at george washington university hospital his wife doris 
said monday 
he went out jogging got a paper and then came back to go with 
me to church everything was fine mrs mcclory said then it 
happened he just collapsed and never came out of it 
mcclory was the secondranking republican on the house judiciary 
committee during congressional hearings on the breakin at the 
democratic national committee headquarters in the watergate complex 
in washington 
although he was a gop loyalist mcclory was one of the leading 
house supporters of an article of impeachment in 1974 charging 
nixon with abusing his constitutional powers in the watergate 
matter he drafted another article charging the president with 
contempt of congress for resisting subpoenas 
i feel really torn mcclory said in an interview at the 
time but im disassociating this job from my relationship with 
the president on philosophy and policies 
during the impeachment hearings mcclory said he was not 
convinced that nixon was directly involved in the watergate coverup 
but rejected suggestions that he had a partisan obligation to 
defend the president against all of the accusations 
i have heard it said by some that they cannot understand how a 
republican could vote to impeach a republican president he said 
in the committees opening debate on impeachment let me hasten 
to assert that that argument demeans my role here it would make a 
mockery of our entire inquiry 
nixon resigned the presidency after the committee voted three 
articles of impeachment 
born in riverside ill mcclory graduated from dartmouth 
college and chicagokent school of law and practiced law in the 
chicago area until 1950 when he was elected to the illinois house 
of representatives he served in the state senate from 1952 to 1962 
while in congress mcclory was a house manager of the equal 
rights amendment and a sponsor of legislation providing that 
federal holidays such as labor day and memorial day be celebrated 
on monday 
mcclorys congressional district in the northern and western 
suburbs of chicago was eliminated by reapportionment in 1981 
rather than opposing incumbent rep john porter also a republican 
in the expanded 10th district he chose not to seek reelection in 
1982 
he will be best remembered for his leadership during the 
watergate hearings and his abiding commitment to the rule of law 
porter said monday along with tens of thousands of people from 
our area i share a tremendous sense of loss in bobs passing 
mcclory had lived in the nations capital since leaving office 
and was a member of the washington law firm of baker amp mckenzie 
he is survived by his wife two sons and a daughter 
mcclory will be buried friday following a private service in 
illinois his wife said she said a public memorial service was 
scheduled for 11 am saturday at the united methodist church in 
lake bluff ill where he had maintained a home since the 1930s 
</TEXT>
