<TEXT>
sales of existing homes rose in june to the 
highest level in a year and a half as buyers tried to beat out 
rising mortgage interest rates a real estate trade group reported 
monday 
the national association of realtors said existing singlefamily 
homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 378 
million units last month a 53 percent increase over may 
it was the fifth consecutive monthly increase and the highest 
level since homes sold at a rate of 406 million units in december 
1986 
in may sales rose a revised 20 percent to a rate of 359 
million units an earlier estimate had put the gain at 31 percent 
the anticipation of continued rising interest rates convinced 
homebuyers to get into the market now rather than waiting said 
john a tuccillo the trade groups chief economist 
but in fact rates did not increase as much as anticipated 
creating an added incentive for homebuyers he said 
rates for fixedrate 30year mortgages averaged 1046 percent 
last week up only about a half of a percentage point from recent 
lows in march according to the federal home loan mortgage corp 
the average does not include addon fees known as points 
however many analysts are predicting rates will edge up by 
another half or full percentage point by the end of the year 
curtailing sales 
i would not be suprised if july gave us a level perhaps as 
strong as june but i think over the remainder of the year were 
going to see those mortgage interest rates move upward and were 
going to see housing market activity trailing off as a result 
said richard peach an economist with the mortgage bankers 
association of america 
june sales were 56 percent higher than a year ago the first 
time in 12 months that the sales pace beat the previous years mark 
for the first six months existing homes sold at a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 344 million units up from 341 million in 
the last half of 1987 
there were 353 million homes sold for all of last year down 
slightly from 356 million in 1986 which was the best since 1979 
most economists are expecting sales of about 340 million this year 
theres been a clear tapering off but we arent in the 
doldrums we havent had a housing bust by any means said mark 
obrinsky an economist with the us league of savings institutions 
the strong sales came amid other indications of weakness in the 
housing market the annual rate of construction of new 
singlefamily homes during the first half of 1988 was down 64 
percent from the julydecember rate of last year 
peach said much of the demand for new housing that built up when 
interest rates soared early in the 1980s has been satisified he 
said existing homes sales are still relatively high in part because 
of strong job growth and people moving to accept new and better 
jobs 
the june sales increase was led by a rise of 92 percent in the 
south to 143 million units followed by gains of 87 percent in 
the midwest to 100 million units and 78 percent in the west to 
690000 units 
sales declined 28 percent in the northeast to an annual sales 
pace of 700000 units 
the median price of an existing home rose 1800 from may to 
june climbing to 90600 up 20 percent the median price was up 
55 percent from 85900 a year ago 
of the four regions the west had the highest appreciation rate 
over the past year with a median sales price of 125100 up 91 
percent from june 1987 the midwest posted a 73 percent gain to 
70600 while in the northeast the price rose 59 percent to 
146300 in the south home prices increased 43 percent in a year 
to 84100 
