<TEXT>
a 26mile stretch of us highway 64 in 
southeastern tennessee is the first segment of a new national 
forest scenic byways system the agriculture department announced 
monday 
forest service chief f dale robertson said the byway is located 
in the cherokee national forest and passes through scenic areas 
dominated by rock bluffs mountain peaks and lake ocoee 
the biway also offers ready access to whitewater rafting 
boating swimming and historical sites related to the civil war and 
the cherokee indian culture he said 
the program was begun this summer to increase the scenic 
enjoyment of the millions of people who drive through national 
forests each year robertson said 
despite a variety of more active recreational activities 
driving for pleasure remains the most popular in the nations 156 
national forests located in 43 states he said 
various groups are working with the usda agency to place 
interpretive signs develop brochures and provide facilities 
designed to make a drive through the forests more enjoyable 
robertson said 
a spokesman for the agency jay humphreys said he expected 
probably three or four more scenic byways will be designated by 
the end of summer he said nominations are due by oct 1 
the tennessee byway was the first to be nominated and the first 
to be approved humphreys said 
