<TEXT>
cincinnati archbishop daniel e pilarczyk 
underwent a fourhour brain operation monday to seal off a ruptured 
blood vessel that could have killed him if it had not been treated 
his chief surgeon said 
dr john m tew jr a pioneer in laser surgery who conducted 
the operation said pilarczyk could leave the hospital after a week 
and return to work in four to six weeks 
pilarczyk 53 was listed in good condition 
pilarczyk roman catholic archbishop since 1982 in the 
550000member archdiocese of cincinnati suffered the aneurysm 
near the base of his brain saturday while vacationing in 
gatlinburg tenn he was transported to the university of tennessee 
hospital in knoxville for initial treatment then was moved by 
helicopter sunday to good samaritan hospital in cincinnati a 
catholic hospital 
pilarczyk survived because his hemorrhaging stopped after the 
rupture and because of good treatment he received at the tennessee 
hospital tew told a news conference monday 
i really felt today like i was being guided i never saw an 
operation go so smoothly said tew chairman of neurosurgery at 
good samaritan 
tew said the medical team cut into pilarczyks skull and used 
two 5millimeter stainless steel clips to seal off the aneurysm a 
sac formed when a weakened blood vessel wall bulges that should 
prevent another rupture tew said 
doctors have bypassed the artery and rerouted the brains blood 
supply to another artery 
pilarczyk has an excellent prognosis and shows no signs of 
paralysis or other damage tew said 
there is no damage to the brain itself tew said he 
doesnt seem to have any trouble at all right now 
tew said the aneurysm is the result of a congenital weakness in 
the wall of the artery which gets thinner over time about 40000 
americans suffer blood vessel ruptures each year and approximately 
15000 of them die as a result 
auxiliary bishop james garland is running the archdiocese in 
pilarczyks absence 
