<DOCNO> AP880725-0160 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
microscopic defects in the bodys 
energygenerating system have been shown to cause blindness and 
might also cause major diseases of the heart brain liver and 
kidneys a researcher said monday 
douglas c wallace of the emory university medical school in 
atlanta said his research is the first to link a specific disease 
to defects in tiny chemical factories called mitochondria which 
convert food into energy to support living cells 
wallace has for years been pursuing the notion that defects in 
mitochondrial genes could be important in many human diseases and 
now he says he has proved his case 
in a research paper that has been submitted to a journal for 
publication wallace said he demonstrates a link between a precise 
pinpoint mitochondrial defect and a rare inherited disease known as 
lhon which can lead to blindness 
i feel now statistically this is the right answer wallace 
said at the jackson laboratory in bar harbor where he is helping 
to teach a course in genetics 
dr berkeley powell associate professor at the oregon health 
sciences university in portland who is familiar with wallaces 
research said i think it is an important step but people have 
been suspecting this for a long time so i dont think its 
revolutionary 
the work is certainly very good and demonstrates it the link 
very nicely powell said 
the disease called lebers hereditary optic neuropathy or lhon 
is very rare wallace said but he has also linked mitochondrial 
defects to several other rare genetic diseases and he is convinced 
that these defects will be shown to be the cause of some major 
degenerative diseases for which the cause has not yet been found 
mitochondria are tiny structures inside cells that convert 
carbohydrates into energycarrying molecules that can be dispatched 
around the cell to keep its machinery running and keep it alive 
each mitochondrion has a tiny set of 13 known genes that are 
entirely separate from the genes and chromosomes that carry most 
hereditary information and that are responsible for most 
hereditary diseases 
the mitochondrial genes are passed on to offspring only by 
mothers through their eggs sperm carry only a few mitochondria 
and those mitochondria are not incorporated into the developing 
offspring 
furthermore they reproduce and mutate rapidly compared with 
other genes and thus the diseases they cause can appear and 
disappear in individuals and in succeeding generations wallace 
said thats why it was so difficult to prove that they were 
causing disease 
wallace said that cyanide is known to poison people by damaging 
their mitochondrial genes cyanide causes disorders of the brain 
heart liver kidneys and muscle he said 
it may therefore be possible that genetic defects in the 
mitochondria can also cause such disorders he said 
in particular he mentioned cardiomyopathy a gradual weakening 
of the heart muscle for which there is no cure except for a heart 
transplant its cause is unknown 
because mitochondria reproduce and mutate rapidly it is 
possible that defects that appear during an individuals lifetime 
can trigger this harmful degeneration in the heart he said 
wallace emphasized that with the exception of the few rare 
disorders to which he has linked the mitochondria his ideas about 
the role of mitochondria in disease are speculation 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880725-0161 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the senate on monday thwarted two attempts by 
sen jesse helms to eliminate or restrict the federal family 
planning program denounced by the north carolina republican as 
evidence of the government going out of control 
the senate voted 6521 to kill a helms amendment that would have 
deleted the 140 million title x family planning program from a 
spending bill for the departments of labor health and human 
services and education 
the chamber voted 5434 to kill another helms amendment that 
would have barred all spending by hhs unless the secretary required 
by jan 31 that unmarried dependent minors 17 or under have written 
parental consent to get contraceptives or prescriptions for 
contraceptives from federally funded clinics 
the senate also approved by voice vote a conscience clause 
saying none of the money in the bill can be used to require any 
person or entity to perform or facilitate abortions the provision 
applies to medical personnel or denominational hospitals with 
religious or moral objections to abortion 
the amendments arose during consideration of the 137 billion 
appropriations bill for the three departments the money is for 
fiscal 1989 which begins oct 1 
title x provides money to states local health departments and 
private groups for family planning clinics serving primarily 
lowincome women 
helms alleged that planned parenthood a major recipient of 
title x money is using federal funds for abortionrelated services 
and that in the last 10 years title x money has been used for 
secret sex programs for our nations teenagers 
the federal government takes money from american parents and 
then uses that money to give contraceptives to their 
children helms said this is wrong this is immoral this is 
evidence of the federal government going out of control and moving 
far beyond what our founding fathers had in mind 
title x is not an abortion program its a knowledge 
program rejoined sen lowell weicker rconn i wish it were 
that all teenagers would go to their parents for advice in this 
area but the fact is they dont there are those situations 
where there is no home then who does the job 
sen james exon dneb said lawmakers like himself who oppose 
abortion should not handicap family planning clinics in any way 
wed be taking a step backwards in the wrong direction by 
requiring parental consent he said we would have more and more 
unwanted and unplanned babies 
exon and sen lawton chiles dfla chairman of the laborhhs 
appropriations subcommittee urged senators to vote their 
convictions on the helms amendments and not cave in to political 
pressure 
we all know in our heart of hearts how we ought to stand on 
it chiles said of the parental consent amendment its a 
question of how we are recorded on it are you going to trigger 
some group against you or not 
the abortion amendment was sponsored by sen gordon humphrey 
rnh who said socalled conscience clauses currently are written 
into some laws but not others 
