<TEXT>
emilio ponce a combattempered 
colonel who is a frontrunner to be armed forces commander says 
the militarys chief aim in el salvadors civil war should be 
winning the loyalty of the rural poor not killing guerrillas 
he said in an interview at his 3rd brigade headquarters in this 
provincial capital 85 miles east of san salvador that soldiers 
should help improve living standards for the rural poor campesinos 
as they are called 
build a coop and set up a chickenraising enterprise teach 
them how to plant vegetables the raising of pigs he said 
these are cheap projects more immediate the people see problems 
resolved more quickly and it leaves them with a tool they can use 
for life 
ponce 41 the commander of the 3rd brigade added that he has 
set aside some of his troops for that purpose and indicated he 
believed similar efforts should be made all around the countryside 
by the military 
highranking military sources say he is the most likely officer 
to succeed gen adolfo blandon as chief of the joint chiefs of 
staff when blandon retires in the coming months 
ponce said he uses two kinds of military units in his command 
one is eminently operative for carrying out offensive 
military operations that principally strike guerrilla commanders 
at different levels these are units trained for night operations 
ambushes and longrange patrols the other type of unit carries out 
first a military role but then fulfills a political function he 
explained 
we cannot think that solely by military means we are going to 
resolve this war even if we kill all the subversives the problem 
will not end such deplorable socioeconomic conditions would 
remain that it the insurgency could easily revive 
this is an ideological and psychological war a war for the 
masses and a war of oganization 
of the political work he added you always have to give the 
campesinos something concrete because they cant eat words 
referring to two previous and unsuccessful development 
projects designed by us advisers to win over the populace he 
said its no longer a matter of building schools or paving 
roads what were doing requires less sophistication and less 
bureaucracy 
ponce said his strategy is producing positive results in his 
eastern command zone 
but two commanders of the guerrillas farabundo marti liberation 
front known as the fmln contended in interviews broadcast by the 
rebels clandestine radio venceremos that an army that represents 
el salvadors status quo can never win the poor farmers heart 
commander jorge melendez said the fact that rebel forces are 
still active in all of the countrys 14 provinces although 
outnumbered 81 by government troops means the army has failed 
militarily 
the root of this failure is in the nature of the fmln which 
arises precisely from those same popular sectors he said 
rebel commander francisco mena sandoval said in a separate 
interview in june the objectives in the mind of each combatant 
have to be expressions of the true interests of his people and 
thats why neither defense minister gen carlos vides casanova 
nor the americans could ever convert the rural poor to the cause 
of foreign interests that have nothing to do with our particular 
problems 
the rural poor make up 60 percent of el salvadors population of 
51 million 
four us army experts who studied el salvador also see the key 
to the war as lying with the loyalty of the rural poor 
cols james hallums richard white aj bacevich and thomas 
young addressed the subject in a paper they wrote in march at 
harvard university titled american military policy in small 
wars the case of el salvador 
of the campaign for the allegiance of the populace the officers 
concluded that disappointment with the outcome of previous 
efforts convinced hardcore salvadoran commanders to forget about 
hearts and minds in favor of pursuing guerrillas 
of the us role the paper says despite their appreciation 
that winning popular support remains as the ultimate strategic aim 
in counterinsurgency american officials have yet to devise 
adequate mechanisms to achieve that aim 
