<TEXT>
a sea of fadedgreen tents has become 
home for 165000 refugees mostly women children and old men of 
a stalemated war in the desert of nearby western sahara 
fourcolor flags of the selfproclaimed sahrawi arab democratic 
republic flutter in the hot wind over banners and grafitti 
proclaiming the republics slogan the entire homeland or 
martyrdom 
the united nations and international relief organizations have 
been feeding and housing the refugees for more than a decade 
the refugees wait here in algeria for something to happen in the 
war between morocco and the marxistled polisario guerrilla 
movement for control of the western sahara formerly spanish sahara 
the algeriabacked polisario movement set up the sahrawi 
republic in 1976 after spain turned western sahara over to morocco 
and mauritania the latter has since withdrawn 
although the sahrawi republic won diplomatic recognition from 
more than 70 countries mostly in the third world it has been 
unable to gain a permanent foothold in the mineralrich territory 
the war has reached a stalemate and the guerrillas now talk of a 
compromise settlement but prospects seem distant and sporadic 
fighting continues 
polisario officials contend the refugees in camps near this 
algerian oasis represent virtually the entire population of the 
disputed territory 
spain held the western sahara until 1975 mainly to protect the 
nearby spanish canary islands little effort was made to develop 
the wilderness an area about the size of colorado spanish 
colonial records indicate the territory had a population of only 
75000 when spain pulled out 
at least 50000 now live under moroccan rule frequently 
proclaiming their loyalty to moroccos king hassan ii 
morocco maintains that more than threefourths of the tindouf 
refugees are not from western sahara but from neighboring 
mauritania niger mali and other impoverished countries on the 
fringes of the sahara desert 
arabicspeaking moslems they originally were nomads herding 
goats and camels over unmarked boundaries often not even aware 
which country they were in 
mahmoud hussein a highschool pupil studying in algiers spoke 
of the culture shock he experiences in traveling between the dual 
worlds of modern algiers and his family tent near tindouf 
i live in algiers nine months of the year and i hate it and 
long for my family he said sitting recently in the brightly 
decorated tent beside his younger sister habiba then when i 
come here for the three months of the summer im dying to return 
he shares his perplexity with hundreds of young people who 
travel to universities in cuba or spain 
polisario officials have set up a system to prevent loss of a 
national and cultural identity among the young and to reinforce 
their motivation to fight 
the young teach the old how to read and write said mohammed 
mahmoud a school teacher the old teach them history and 
tradition so as to enforce their sense of identity 
from age 9 the children also receive basic military training in 
preparation for automatic conscription after high school of boys 
who dont go on to university 
tindouf a military zone is 1000 miles southwest of algiers 
the refugee camps begin about two miles west of tindouf their 
rows of canvas tents and adjacent stone kitchens spread in clusters 
over the stark landscape 
at a camp hospital dr khadigetto alawi said she had just 
returned from five years of medical training in havana cuba she 
said she and the other hospital staff receive no salaries 
polisario officials said no one receives any pay including the 
16000man guerrilla army and 70000 officials a few raise goats 
and sheep for their own use they said 
a woman who identified herself as humayed welcomed a group of 
visiting reporters into the tent she shares with six women and 
children of her family she said their menfolk were at the 
front 120 miles away 
the women have an important role while the men are away at 
war said a roman catholic priest who goes by the name father 
gonzales and works for the caritas relief organization 
they marry young so as to have many children and they also 
undergo military training themselves we try to teach them the 
importance of motherchild care they concentrate a lot on 
preventive medicine 
a polisario official said it is expected that young war widows 
remarry quickly in order to maintain population growth ghalouha 
elsalm a war widowbride said she has spent the nine years since 
she lost her husband rearing a daughter but now is marrying again 
i have to continue having children she said explaining 
that it was a national requirement 
most of the women said they long to return to the western sahara 
and its cool atlantic breezes when the war is over 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

