<TEXT>
fertile soil is sparse in egypt just 6 
million acres along the nile and the government is cracking down 
on those who use it to make bricks 
at a brickyard here one recent day workers swarmed like bees 
over a kiln as they dismantled a brickyard that had fallen victim 
to the government order 
the governments intend is to preserve egypts arable land to 
help feed an exploding population now 53 million and growing at a 
rate of 12 million a year 
after five years of loose application of a law banning the use 
of fertile topsoil to make bricks the government in december set a 
sixmonth deadline and recently sent police out to see that an 
estimated 1700 affected brickyards indeed close down 
we admit that this is the first time the law has been 
effective said farouk zaki head of the department responsible 
for land protection at the agriculture ministry 
the owners realized that we were serious this time and all the 
brickyards stopped functioning on deadline without violence 
the decree requires brickyard owners to switch from the ageold 
process of making bricks by hand with topsoil to a mechanized one 
that makes bricks only with pure clay thus eliminating the use of 
topsoil 
violators of the topsoil ban face six months in prison and a 
fine 
officials acknowledged that the decree has troublesome 
sideeffects a growing black market in bricks and unemployment for 
about 70000 workers 
only 41 of the dismantled brickyards so far have switched to the 
mechanized method at a cost the equivalent in egyptian pounds of 
13000 to 650000 zaki said he added that 200 others were 
expected to follow suit 
at the moment the price of bricks is rising steeply because 
of the law enforcement said mohammed ramez responsible for 
buildingmaterial control at the housing ministry 
he said black market prices of the machineproduced bricks are 
double the official 30 for 1000 
we expect to have a complete balance between supply and demand 
within five years ramez added the enforcement of the law he 
said has resulted in a shortage of 2 billion to 3 billion bricks 
this year 
officials estimate that about 4500 acres of arable land have 
become unproductive in the last 20 years because topsoil was 
stripped for bricks the loss is considerable for a country that 
produces only 40 percent of its food and must import the rest to 
feed its burgeoning population 
some people used to remove earth down to 10 meters 30 
feet said zaki of the agriculture ministry any removal 
weakens the soil taking away essential nutrients and raises the 
water table 
we are requiring owners to reclaim their land at a cost of 
10000 to 15000 pounds 4300 to 6500 per acre zaki said 
he estimated this would take at least two years 
the removal of topsoil began in the early 1970s after the high 
dam at aswan went into operation and held back flood waters bearing 
tons of silt that originally was used in the brick industry 
as construction boomed in egypt and the demand for bricks 
skyrocketed some farmers abandoned their crops to make as much as 
70 times more money by selling topsoil or making bricks on their 
own 
earth bricks brought us enormous profits said ahmed 
aburawash a former brickyard owner in giza 
in a good month i would make 3000 pounds 1300 with earth 
from one of my acres 
he maintained that no harm is done to land scraped two meters 
about six feet deep anything can be planted on it 
aburawash has switched to raising cattle and has turned most of 
his brickyard into a banana plantation which he said brings only a 
quarter of the profit he made from bricks 
his employees whose numbers have been trimmed from 50 to 20 
were busy one recent day dismantling one kiln with 22 others to be 
taken down in the neighborhood 
they were worried about their future 
this is my first day of work since all the brickyards shut 
down last month abdelhamid sharafeddin said 
i will work on the other kilns and then who knows people like 
me are pushed aside i know nothing but brickmaking 
</TEXT>
