<TEXT>
land reform the most radical 
and expensive government project in el salvadors history has 
benefited more than half a million people since its inception in 
1980 and is radically changing the social structure of the 
countryside 
despite major shortcomings the program has redistributed 30 
percent of the countrys arable land after compensating former 
owners the 520000 people who have received land either as 
individuals or members of cooperatives make up a quarter of the 
countrys rural poor 
the program however is beset by such problems as flagging 
production tight credit deficient administration and alleged 
corruption it is also hampered by el salvadors guerrilla war 
land reform was designed principally by us officials as a 
means of undercutting the leftist guerrillas in their efforts to 
win the sympathy of the rural poor 
a dozen government and military officials cooperativists 
peasants and international development officials interviewed said 
while the toughest years of land reform are past obstacles remain 
in extending it and ensuring its smooth running 
some former landowners have not abandoned the idea of 
recovering their lands and with them real power they recall with 
nostalgia their wealth said francisco flores president of the 
salvadoran institute for agrarian transformation the government 
body primarily responsible for land reform 
but he added that the vast majority of the former owners have 
accepted compensation and that title to the property has been 
legally transferred 
the process has cost almost 300 million most of it provided by 
the united states 
agrarian reform is enshrined in the 1983 constitution which 
would have to be scrapped if big holdings were to again be 
concentrated in few hands 
some leftofcenter cooperativists and officials of the 
governing christian democratic party are concerned that the right 
wing which won control of the legislature in march elections 
might try to undo some of the reform 
the rightist republican nationalist alliance known as arena is 
considered in a good position to challenge the christian democrats 
in presidential elections scheduled for march 
orlando arevalo director of the national finance entity for 
agricultural lands said a marked increase has been noted in 
expulsions of land reform beneficiaries in recent months he blames 
former owners emboldened by arenas legislative victory and 
prospects for gaining the presidency next year 
most landholders are licensed to carry arms arevalo said 
the former owners who have always opposed the reform are now 
encouraged and are fighting the campesinos politically juridically 
and by force 
but he said virtually all of the 500 or so recent expulsions 
were from small holdings and represent a tiny percentage of the 
reformed sector he said the government is resorting to the courts 
and the military to get the small farmers reinstated 
he noted however that the judiciary has been dominated for 
decades by the rightwingers who might favor the landowners 
phase i of land reform expropriated all holdings over 1235 
acres involving 477 properties owned by 262 families a subsequent 
landtothetiller law affected small holdings and benefited about 
45000 families 
the phase i lands were converted into 329 cooperatives 25 of 
which have been abandoned because they are in war zones about 
30000 families live and work on the 304 phase i cooperatives 
according to flores and international development officials 
working with the reform a third of the cooperatives are able to 
finance operations pay debts and dividends to their members 
another third are described as bankrupt basket cases that 
cannot succeed in their current structure 
the remaining third are described as borderline 
arenas platform calls for the dismantling of all but the most 
successful cooperatives dividing the unsuccessful and borderline 
ventures into parcels that would be transferred by title to the 
farmers working them the party contends that only by converting el 
salvador into a country of property owners will there be 
sufficient incentive and initiative to spur production 
the christian democrats after seeing many millions of dollars 
lost have already begun dividing up the failed cooperatives into 
family plots 
the political decision is to divide said flores 
one divided venture is the 2100acre la normandia cooperative 
usulutan province 65 miles southeast of san salvador before being 
expropriated from dona maria de dalton in 1980 it produced cotton 
for export with small sections dedicated to the corn and beans 
consumed by the peasants who worked it 
two months into this years growning season with abundant rains 
after two years of drought it is a green sea of thighhigh corn 
divided in 85acre plots it is home for 170 families who live in 
mudbrick tileroofed houses with wells but without running water 
or electricity it has a school but no clinic 
a mile into the fields along an oxentrod path marcial lopez 
worked with his wife maria and two of their eight children tending 
tomato plants along the edge of their plot most of which was sown 
with corn 
lopez talked of his years in the landreform program 
from 80 to 86 we had credit from the government and we 
planted cotton but we only showed losses those who are up in arms 
the guerrillas would attack each year right before we were going 
to spray and destroy or damage the plants without pesticide the 
crop was always bad he said 
part of the guerrillas strategy is to sabotage of the national 
economy which is heavily dependent on exports of coffee sugar and 
cotton 
the cooperative decided last year to divide the land into family 
plots leaving some fallow and some to be rented or parceled out to 
eventual new beneficiaries of the agricultural reform 
asked if hed prefer to continue working as part of a 
cooperative or have title to his plot lopez responded both ways 
are good individually if we have financing we would probably 
make the land produce more but the cooperative could also produce 
good results under better conditions and it would provide more 
work for more people 
the cooperative is considered one of the basketcases 
</TEXT>
