<DOCNO> AP880725-0222 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
 
editors note is a child who is hard of hearing more likely to 
become a criminal later in life studies in the nations prisons 
suggest there is a link thomas crowe of the university of 
mississippi is one researcher who believes that dealing with 
hearing disorders in young children may help reduce crime 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
noting an unusually high percentage of 
prisoners who are hard of hearing almost half in mississippi 
some researchers suspect the disorder may contribute to criminal 
behavior 
my working hypothesis is that hearing loss may be the first 
link in a chain of events or circumstances that eventually lead to 
a life of crime says thomas crowe chairman of the university of 
mississippi department of communicative disorders 
crowe found that 485 percent of the inmates at the mississippi 
state penitentiary at parchman suffer some kind of hearing disorder 
compared with only 7 percent among the general public the 
statistics are even more startling because the 7 percent represents 
the entire general population from infants to the elderly however 
the average age of the prison population is 25 and the younger age 
group should have a lower percentage of hearing disorders 
other researchers have had similar findings an ohio state 
penitentiary study in 1970 indicated 40 percent of the inmates had 
hearing disorders a 1986 study in wisconsin cited 36 percent and a 
1979 study in virginia 17 percent 
the ultimate question crowe says is what impact has the 
hearing loss had on that persons life has that hearing loss in 
any way contributed directly or indirectly to the persons 
criminal behavior and how do you determine that 
crowes research team which includes an audiologist 
psychologist psychiatrist medical doctor and linguist is now 
applying to the us justice department for a grant for a 
fiveyear followup study 
the second study will determine the severity nature and causes 
of inmates hearing disorders he said the amount of the request 
has yet to be worked out 
corrections officials as well as audiologists and speech 
pathologists nationwide are concerned about the high level of 
hearing disorders among prison populations says jo williams 
manager of audiology and technical assistance for the american 
speechlanguagehearing association in rockville md the 
56000member organization is the largest association of 
audiologists and speech and language pathologists in the nation 
the association called for more research in the field after a 
task forces cursory look at the problem in 1984 
the task force cited a nationwide survey of about 200 state and 
federal corrections administrators which indicated 77 percent of 
those polled believe the psychological and communication problems 
stemming from hearing disorders lead to criminal behavior 
crowe says he has found only a few dozen studies conducted in 
the past 40 years on any aspect of prisoners hearing and speech 
disorders of the few studies available he says almost all have 
merely documented the prevalence of problems 
if the hearing disorder is congenital or occurred early in the 
inmates life crowe says its likely the handicap helped shape a 
criminal personality 
crowes initial research in 1985 didnt indicate the exact 
nature severity or causes of the hearing disorders because there 
wasnt enough money for detailed hearing tests or medical 
evaluations 
the initial study involved merely testing each parchman inmates 
hearing at different frequencies and comparing that to a normal 
persons hearing range 
crowe compares the initial auditory screening test to a simple 
eye chart used by an opthalmologist the doctor knows the patient 
cant see the letters at a certain size but more tests are needed 
for a diagnosis of the problem 
there could be many causes for the hearing disorders crowe 
says including heredity and loud noises as well as lack of medical 
attention to ear infections or other problems in childhood 
even relatively minor hearing losses could damage a childs 
personality development crowe says many children with undetected 
hearing disorders grow up without ever knowing theyre physically 
different from their peers however they must deal with 
considerably more stress and disorientation 
it may sound like mumbling crowe says it would be like 
you trying to interact with someone with a very heavy foreign 
accent if you have to listen to them for a long time it will tire 
you out you have to channel and focus your attention to 
comprehend 
the strain may make the child irritable and he may appear to 
have an extremely short attention span 
some children with undetected hearing losses may grow up able to 
capture words but the emotions attached to the words escape them 
crowe says 
consider a preschool child who has a hearing loss not a real 
terrible hearing loss the child learns to talk but it is severe 
enough that the child has trouble hearing the meaning of things 
crowe says 
not only do you hear what is said but you hear how its said 
you hear inflections things like that you can read my moods and 
emotions 
an inability to follow the emotional trains of thought of others 
could trigger all kinds of antisocial tendencies crowe says add 
the emotional and intellectual handicaps from a hearing disorder to 
the underprivileged status of many children and you get a prime 
candidate for prison he says 
if that scenario is sometimes correct theoretically we can 
sometimes prevent crime by dealing with hearing problems and 
language problems at a preschool age he says 
some preschool programs such as head start do some hearing 
screening but many children dont have hearing tests until 
kindergarten or much later after personality traits are long 
entrenched 
i didnt have my first hearing test until i got back from 
vietnam crowe says 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

