<TEXT>
a think tank has been given 10 months to 
answer a question that has concerned consumers and plagued 
philatelists since the dawn of postal automation why wont stamps 
stick 
battelle memorial institute which recently received a 700000 
contract from the us postal service convenes a meeting here 
thursday in hopes of making a sticky situation stickier said don 
mcdowell general manager of the stamp division of the us postal 
service in washington 
about 100 representatives of adhesive manufacturers and paper 
companies expected to attend the oneday meeting will be asked to 
share their thoughts and in some cases their secret formulas 
i dont think 700000 is too much to pay for a stamp that 
sticks he said in a telephone interview compare that to the 
fact that stamps are an 8 billionayear business 
the columbusbased institute is trying to find a perfect stamp 
glue one that not only will keep stamp and envelope together from 
the point of origin to destination but will taste a little better 
mcdowell said 
the public insists that it at least if it cant stick not 
taste so bad he said the problem is finding a consensus on 
what tastes good some people like liver others dont so its got 
to be something that may not taste great and may not taste like 
anything at all 
he said consumers have repeatedly suggested more flavorful glues 
that taste like cherry vanilla and vodka 
oh they have suggested it but i hardly think vodka would be 
appropriate he said laughing no jerry falwell were not 
planning on that at all 
neither mcdowell nor battelle consider the issue a laughing 
matter 
sure people giggle but its not very funny to us its very 
important to us and to the people who want their letters to reach 
their destinations mcdowell said 
he said battelles task will not be easy 
do you have any idea how many adhesives there are in the 
world he said the postal service uses three kinds of adhesives 
now which mcdowell describes as shiny not shiny and halfway in 
between 
he could not estimate how many stamps are lost in transit every 
year but said the problem has gotten worse since the postal 
service began to automate in the early 1970s 
before then when it was manual the impact to a stamp was 
like a car hitting a brick wall at 5 mph now its like a car 
hitting a brick wall at 60 mph because these machines accelerate 
and decelerate so fast when the envelope stops the stamp doesnt 
want to he said 
slowing the machines wont fix the problem he said the rising 
volume of mailed items means the system will have to speed up 
about 35 million stamped items move through the system every year 
the american philatelic society an organization of stamp 
collectors has argued that not only is the adhesive not sticky 
enough it also eats through the paper which decreases a stamps 
value 
one philatelist does not agree that a new glue is needed 
mw martin of the topical philatelic house in columbus says the 
glue is not the culprit he blames the disappearing stamp dilemma 
on human error and sorting machines that are not stampfriendly 
im in this business 40 years and i just dont see the 
nonsticky problem if they fall off sometimes its not the glue 
people arent licking them enough the envelope maybe has some dust 
on it i think the real problem is the machines at the post 
office he said 
