<TEXT>
shortly after the tokyo stock exchange opened last 
tuesday grimfaced japanese businessmen began filing into the 
lobby of sanyo securities co ltd in the ginza shopping district 
to track the markets performance 
their faces grew grim as a retreat that began the previous day 
in response to a jump in the us dollars value quickly turned 
into a rout 
before it was over the markets barometer the nikkei stock 
average of 225 issues had lost 51309 points its biggest loss of 
the year 
after a brief rebound at midweek the decline resumed 
stripping more than 600 points from the average by weeks end on 
monday the market rose 7655 points at the opening bell then 
slumped again to finish down 11781 at 2718353 
while the declines pale in comparison to the calamitous plunge 
of last october when new york markets set off a worldwide stock 
market panic they are worrisome nonetheless 
some japanese economists view the latest decline as a warning 
shot for the highflying japanese economy and they caution that 
the next black monday could be precipitated here 
i think these are continuing signs of confusion over the 
direction of the economy in japan said william p sterling 
senior economist for merrill lynch securities co in tokyo these 
are warning signals and people are nervous 
market analysts blamed the wave of selling on market shifts 
from steel and shipbuilding shares to electronics 
sterling said investors are trying to take their money into more 
stable stocks so they have a better chance of selling if the 
market falls 
when people have their eyes on the fire exit they buy those 
stocks he said 
the root of the concern appears to be the recent surge in the 
dollars value which has moved above the psychologically important 
level of 130 yen after a long decline some experts here also view 
the recent increase in american interest rates as a precursor of 
higher japanese rates 
the boost in the dollar sprang partly from an improvement in 
american trade statistics which show the imbalance between us 
imports and exports is shrinking that shift while good news for 
american industry threatens to divert the lifeblood of japans 
boom which has drawn its strength from a steady stream of exports 
to the united states 
the united states is seeing the high side of this process 
sterling said of the changing trade relationship but its trading 
partners are beginning to feel the heat this is now beginning to 
show a strain on the japanese economy 
sterling said there was so much growth last year that if the 
japanese economy had zero growth in 1988 it would still be 34 
percent above a year ago 
the japanese governments leading index of economic indicators 
fell two months in a row in march and april a decline two months 
in a row typically has meant a recession in japan within four to 
eight months 
industrial production was down 38 percent for april and may 
which portends zero or negative growth for the second quarter 
housing starts have been falling rapidly following a boom last 
year that raised real estate prices and cooled the enthusiasm of 
prospective home buyers 
the gloomy view is far from universal however last week a 
group of 21 japanese financial institutions issued a glowing report 
on the state of the economy saying growth through the fiscal year 
was expected to be 44 percent to 54 percent 
teruhiko mano an economist for the bank of tokyo said the 
recent market swings are merely an adjustment not an indicator 
of recession he also takes issue with the housing slowdown 
which he says is merely a reaction against prices that were too 
high to begin with 
the dollar went up and the market went down he said of the 
stock market drop our economy is reacting to the capitalistic 
system it shows it is working well 
